The first postulation has been studied by several authors [11,12]. The universal distribution function of the QCD is interpreted as the structure function of the b-quark in the parton model, which determines the distribution of the light-cone projection of the b-quark momentum inside the B meson. In this and the next sections, we present the heavy quark expansion of the model in the viewpoint of the parton model.

Being on a ground of an phenomenological model, the b-quark mass mb is not an ingredient of the model and should be defined in the framework of the model in order to express the phenomenological model as 1=mQ expansion. We define the b-quark mass as:

mb j hximB ; (3) following ref. [12]. Since we have the measured value of mB and well-defined function f (x), this relation explicitly defines the mass of the b-quark. The nonperturbative informations of the parton model are encoded in the distribution function f (x). If we want to express the parton model with the heavy quark expansion, it is performed by expanding the distribution function in 1=mQ. We write the expansion of the distribution function f (x) as

